When the choice was between a friendly dictator (e.g. Marcos) and stable democratic reform, we generally supported the latter.

In other words, yeah, I think the good guys won the Cold War, and I think it matters - a lot.
That's not to dismiss other factors - cultural, military, trade, resources - that are going to weigh in a practical way on relationships.
But the history South Korea - or Taiwan, for that matter - or much of Latin America shows a preferential evolutionary arc towards democracy.
Sometimes (as with China) the results were incredibly positive, beyond our hopes. In other cases (as with Iran), they were disastrous.
The world is not infinitely malleable for us to shape. US had to decide - work with Mao, or not? Work with the Shah, or not?
